  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2590606191" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2590606191" />
    <a title="Saimi Korhonen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/59275887-saimi-korhonen"><img alt="Saimi Korhonen" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1561832552p2/59275887.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2590606191?book_show_action=true">Sep 23, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Saimi Korhonen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Saimi Korhonen" href="/user/show/59275887-saimi-korhonen">Saimi Korhonen</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2590606191" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2007912672996198704"><i> “They say that it is, nothing, that one does not suffer, that it is an easy end; that death in this why is very much simplified. Ah! then, what do they call they call this agony of six weeks, this summing up in one day? What then is the anguish of this irreparable day, which is passing so slowly and yet so fast? What is this ladder of tortures which terminates in the scaffold?” </i><br/><br/>The Last Day of a Condemned Man is narrated by an unnamed man who has been sentenced to die and is writing all his tho</span>
  <span id="freeText2007912672996198704" style="display:none"><i> “They say that it is, nothing, that one does not suffer, that it is an easy end; that death in this why is very much simplified. Ah! then, what do they call they call this agony of six weeks, this summing up in one day? What then is the anguish of this irreparable day, which is passing so slowly and yet so fast? What is this ladder of tortures which terminates in the scaffold?” </i><br /><br />The Last Day of a Condemned Man is narrated by an unnamed man who has been sentenced to die and is writing all his thoughts on his fate, his surroundings and his past life down, hoping that one day his story will be heard and might inspire people to change their minds on the death penalty. The novel was Hugo's way of expressing his desires for the abolition of the death penalty, and it definitely leaves the reader shaken and horrified. The narrator's fear, terror and pain at his impending doom is moving and heartbreaking, and though the book is very short, it packs a punch. I really enjoyed it, as I've enjoyed all of Hugo's works. The Last Day of a Condemned Man is lesser known than Les Misérables or The Hunchback of Notre Dame, but it's a very Hugo novel: it centers around a cruel injustice, the characters are underprivileged people who enjoy no protection or compassion from the society they live in, and the prose is beautiful but also blunt in describing the cruelty of the world the story takes place in. I love Hugo's stories so much, and this one was no exception.<br /><br />There are a lot of standout moments in this story, and I want to mention a few of them. One was that scene when the convicts sentenced to a lifetime of forced labor and our unnamed narrator watches them being gathered to the yard and shackled from his cell. Another moment that really impacted me was the scene between the condemned man and his daughter. The fact that she <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ couldn't remember him anymore, and thought her father had already died broke me. There are these moments in all of Hugo's stories that I'll never be able to forget and that will forever haunt me, and this was definitely one of those.  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> I also just really enjoyed the way the psyche and emotional state of the narrator was described, and how his thoughts on his fate constantly shifted from fear to anger to resignation to grief and back to fear again. My absolute favorite part of the book was definitely Hugo's preface, detailing his opinions on the death penalty, why it's inhumane and should be abolished. That shit was brilliant.<br /><br />Definitely highly recommend this book! This would also be a great starting point with Hugo's works - his books are usually huge and thus they can be quite daunting, but this one is short and contained, but still has all of those elements that make a Hugo novel great.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2007912672996198704" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


